  "summary": "After the lights fail at Miss Blacklock's home, a man with a hoarse, nasal voice enters a room brandishing a flashlight and shouting commands. He fires a revolver twice, and a third shot is heard after a shadow stumbles and collapses. In the ensuing chaos, Miss Blacklock is found with blood trickling from her face, though she claims it is merely a graze from a bullet that passed near her ear.\n\nColonel Eastbrook and Edmund investigate the hallway and find a body. They also rescue Midge from the dining room, where she had been screaming in terror. As the group gathers candles to provide light, the Colonel examines the deceased, who is wearing a black hooded cloak, a mask, and gloves. The Colonel notes the man has golden hair and bloody fingers, suggesting the death may have been an accident or a suicide. Once the lights are restored, the Colonel removes the mask and identifies the man as a young individual. Dora Bunner recognizes him as a man from the Medenham Club who had previously approached Miss Blacklock for money to return to Switzerland. Miss Blacklock maintains her composure, ordering Julia to retrieve medical supplies and instructing Patrick to call the police.\n\nElsewhere, Chief Constable George Ridestad receives a report from Inspector Delmont Corrado regarding the incident. Corrado confirms the deceased is Rudolf Scherz, a Swiss national who worked as a receptionist at the Royal Spa Hotel in Medenham. Corrado intends to investigate both the hotel and the Blacklock mansion.",
